{"page_id": "https://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/02/nyregion/colleges-step-up-recruitment.html", "source": "nyt", "arm": "elections", "window": "1984", "newspaper_title": "The New York Times", "lccn": null, "date": "1984-09-02", "state": null, "city": null, "type_of_material": "News", "section": "New York", "ocr_text": "COLLEGES STEP UP RECRUITMENT\nLONG ISLAND colleges and universities, faced with a shrinking pool of applicants within their own region and forced to compete against one another and with out- of-state schools for students, have stepped up recruiting efforts, turning increasingly to more businesslike methods. \n\nColleges are investing money in sophisticated marketing and public-relations tools to get their message across. Often a school focuses on new facilities or expanded degree programs or says it is offering extra inducements, including extensive financial assistance, and is pioneering in career education for both a traditional student body and an older population. A major thrust of many of the messages is that a particular school is a high-quality institution, with its own distinct identity and with programs reflecting the changing needs of today's society.\n\nAlthough not heavily endowed, most of the Island's private schools, despite general increases in tuition and the tougher competition, are holding their own. Institutions that once served mainly commuter students are adjusting to change. Of course, the situation varies from campus to campus. Some institutions, for example, cannot afford new construction, while others that have expanded housing facilities are advertising for additional dormitory space to accommodate an expected student overflow.", "matched_phrase": "will carry", "cycle": 1984}
